{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"fall-of-rome-476","type":"event","content":{"title":"Fall of the Western Roman Empire","date_label":"476 CE","description":"On **September 4, 476 CE**, the Germanic chieftain **Odoacer** deposed **Romulus Augustulus**, the last emperor of the Western Roman Empire, and sent the imperial regalia to Constantinople. The event that contemporaries barely noticed has since been taken as one of history's great turning points — the formal end of classical antiquity and the beginning of the Middle Ages in Western Europe.\n\nThe actual decline had unfolded over centuries of military pressure, economic contraction, political instability, and pandemic. But 476 provides a clean symbolic marker for a world that had fundamentally changed: the Mediterranean-spanning administrative structure that had endured for five centuries was gone, replaced by a patchwork of Germanic kingdoms.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["rome","romulus-augustulus","odoacer","fall-of-rome","western-empire","476"],"sources":[{"title":"Fall of the Western Roman Empire — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/sack-of-Rome-476"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"476","precision":"year"},"significance":{"value":970,"temporal_scope":"centuries","geographic_scope":"western-europe"}}}
